    "visualization": "<div class=\"viz-container\"><h4>Database Types Comparison</h4><div class=\"viz-canvas\" style=\"flex-direction:column;gap:8px\"><table class=\"viz-table\"><thead><tr><th>Type</th><th>Structure</th><th>Language</th><th>Best For</th><th>C++ Analogy</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td>Relational</td><td>Tables</td><td>SQL</td><td>Banking, ERP</td><td>vector&lt;struct&gt;</td></tr><tr><td>Key-Value</td><td>Dictionary</td><td>GET/SET</td><td>Caching, Sessions</td><td>unordered_map</td></tr><tr><td>Document</td><td>JSON Docs</td><td>BSON queries</td><td>Social, CMS</td><td>map&lt;string,map&gt;</td></tr><tr><td>Graph</td><td>Nodes+Edges</td><td>Cypher</td><td>Social graphs</td><td>adjacency list</td></tr></tbody></table></div></div>",
    "whyMatters": "Knowing which database type to use is a critical engineering skill. The wrong choice can lead to poor performance, wasted storage, or impossible queries. Every major tech company uses multiple database types together.",
